# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: admission-controllers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:admission-controllers/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:admission-controllers/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:admission-controllers/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:admission-controllers/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The most well known policy-based management architecture was specified jointly by the IETF and the DMTF.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] This consists of four main functional elements: the Policy Management Tool (PMT), Policy Repository, Policy Decision Point (PDP), and Policy Enforcement Point (PEP).
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The PMT is used by an administrator to define or update the policies to be enforced in the managed network.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Resulting policies are stored in a repository in a form that must correspond to an information model so as to ensure interoperability across products from different vendors.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] When new policies have been added in the repository, or existing ones have been changed, the PMT issues the relevant PDP with notifications, which in turn interprets the policies and communicates them to the PEP.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The latter is a component that runs on a policy-aware node and can execute (enforce) the different policies.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The components of the architecture can communicate with each other using a variety of protocols.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The preferred choice for communicating policy decisions between a PDP and network devices (PEPs) is the Common Open Policy Service (COPS) or SNMP, and LDAP for the PMT/PDP–repository communication.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The simplest approach for policy specification is through a sequence of rules, in which each rule is the form of a simple condition-action pair.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The conditional part of the rule can be a simple or compound expression specified in either conjunctive or disjunctive normal form.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The action part of the rule can be a set of actions that must be executed when the conditions are true.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The IETF does not define a specific language to express network policies but rather a generic object-oriented information model for representing policy information.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] This model is a generic one, specifying the structure of abstract policy classes by means of association, thus allowing vendors to implement their own set of conditions and actions to be used by the policy rules.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] As with any programmable system, a policy-driven one can suffer from inconsistencies incurred by contradicting rules governing its behaviour.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] These are known as policy conflicts and come about as a result of specification errors, omissions, or contradictory management operations and, in some cases, can have catastrophic effects on the operation of the managed system.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] They have also been described as being analogous to software bugs that occur when two or more policies are activated simultaneously enforcing contradictory management operations on the system.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Policy conflicts are broadly classified into domain-independent and application-specific, where the former, as the names suggest, are independent of the policy application, and the latter are bound by the constraints of the application domain.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Example application domains that have been considered in the literature include quality of service (QoS) in IP networks, distributed systems, firewall security, and call control in telecommunication networks.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] For example, conflicts can occur between policies for dynamically allocating resources and those setting quotas for users or classes of service.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] As such, automation should be a key aspect of dynamic analysis mechanisms so that the operational impact of a conflict can be kept to a minimum.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] To effectively use policies and drive the functionality of a managed system in a consistent manner, it is necessary to check that newly created policies do not conflict with each other or with policies already deployed in the system.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] To achieve this, detection processes utilise information regarding the conditions under which conflicts can arise to search policy spaces and identify policies that meet the conflict criteria.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Based on the types of conflicts identified in the literature and the different application domains in which they occur, research has concentrated in the development of mechanisms and techniques for their effective detection.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Popular approaches for the detection of conflicts have been based on: meta-policies (detection rules), policy relationships, applicability spaces, and information models.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Resolution is the latter part of policy analysis, which aims at handling detected inconsistencies, preferably in an automated manner, so that consistency among policies can be restored.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The process of resolving conflicts may involve retracting, suppressing, prioritising, or amending policies, and in some cases, enforcing a new policy altogether so that consistency among policy rules can be restored.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The methodology in doing so depends heavily on the type of policies involved and the domain in which conflicts occur.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Although human intervention is unavoidable in some situations, several research efforts focussed on techniques to automate the resolution process where possible.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Popular approaches for the resolution of conflicts have been based on: meta-policies (resolution rules), precedence, policy ordering, and conflict prevention.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The time-frame at which conflicts can be detected influences the analysis methodology and requirements for dealing with them.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Static conflicts are typically detected through analysis initiated manually by the system administrator; conflicts represent inconsistencies between policies and are typically resolved by amending the policies.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] In contrast, run-time conflicts must be detected by a process that monitors policy enforcement and detects inconsistent situations in the system’s execution.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Resolution must be achieved automatically, for example through enforcing resolution rules.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Lack of automation in the handling of run-time conflicts may have catastrophic consequences on the correct system operation, especially when managing QoS for delay sensitive applications.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Ideally, a policy-based management system should facilitate the definition of high-level administrative goals, which are easy for humans to express and understand, enable their translation into low-level policies and map them into commands that configure the managed devices accordingly.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] While the high-level goals reflect the business objectives of the network administrator, the low-level policies are responsible for device-level configurations.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Policy refinement is the process of transforming a high-level goal or abstract policy specification into low-level, concrete policies that can be enforced on the managed system.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] Several policy refinement approaches have been developed.
[src:admission-controllers/policy-based-management] The most notable ones are based on linear temporal logic, event calculus, and utility computing.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] In web development, a **webhook** is a method of augmenting or altering the behavior of a web page or web application with custom callbacks.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] These callbacks may be maintained, modified, and managed by third-party users who need not be affiliated with the originating website or application.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] In 2007, Jeff Lindsay coined the term *webhook* from the computer programming term *hook*.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] Webhooks are "user-defined HTTP callbacks".
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] They are usually triggered by some event, such as pushing code to a repository, a purchase, a comment being posted to a blog and many more use cases.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] When that event occurs, the source site makes an HTTP request to the URL configured for the webhook.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] Users can configure them to cause events on one site to invoke behavior on another.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] Common uses are to trigger builds with continuous integration systems or to notify bug tracking systems.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] Because webhooks use HTTP, they can be integrated into web services without adding new infrastructure.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] When the client (the originating website or application) makes a webhook call to the third-party user's server, the incoming POST request should be authenticated to avoid a spoofing attack and its timestamp verified to avoid a replay attack.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] The sender may choose to keep a constant list of IP addresses from which requests will be sent.
[src:admission-controllers/webhook] This is not a sufficient security measure on its own, but it is useful for when the receiving endpoint is behind a firewall or NAT.
